Anonymous Tue 14 Dec 2021 03:00:02 No.43936379 Report
Quoted By:
>>43935948
Keep chapters short and with as few characters as possible.
Most stories use way too much dialogue. Unless you're writing a mystery or a procedural where there are a lot of interviews, talking too much just slows down the pace to a crawl. Too many characters in one place also means everyone needs a reason to be there.
Two to five people make up a good argument/discussion that increases plot tension.

>>43935990
>>43936050
>>43936121
Here's how to do it, or my favorite way.
Talk out your dialogue with a stopwatch.
Ask yourself when you'd get bored of listening to someone else or be tired of them arguing with you.
Grab a piece of paper and write down what are the three most important bits of info the reader needs to get out of the conversation. If that's not the majority of the dialogue, summarize the rest.
Also, lay back and use dialogue-free bits of time to explore the sensory side of your setting. In the case of SoL, say your two characters are on a bus together. They stopped talking minutes ago. Describe the weather outside by how the sunlight plays over the characters. mention them leaning against each other or holding hands. Have another non-speaking character take notice of them, and the main ones realize they're being watched.

Pacing isn't easy, but you control it by word/sentence/paragraph length.

Anonymous Tue 14 Dec 2021 03:00:08 No.43936383 Report
Quoted By: >>43936457
>>43936260
Action is definitely difficult. Too specific and detailed and you can lose the pacing or the reader's attention. Combat, smut, whatever. You have to strike some sort of balance, and usually it comes down to the mood/theme you want to impart with the action. Dueling as an example probably needs to feel more like a conversation than very specific descriptions of their foot placement.
To some readers, the very specific way your made up spaceship does it's launch sequence may be super interesting, to others it may be really fucking boring and irrelevant.
It all comes down to striking that balance and it aint easy.

Since I played most in the original...
I is an oddball because many of the things we think of as FF tropes or mechanics didn't start to evolve until II or III at the earliest. But for its time it was a massive game and a game-changer.
II was even odder, and the hints of what we'd see in IV & V started there. As the NES and Famicom used coprocs in the cartridge, this just felt different from the first minute. I actually liked the combat and leveling system as you had to think more.
III had the first hints of what Uematsu could do if you unleashed him on the audio hardware, and the system was wildly flexible. It was one of those titles that grew on me. If you want hints of the strategy that the first Tactics game ran with, here it is.
